// content/y10/history/islands/x07.js — Year 10 History Topic 7 expansion: Power & the People (extra flashcards + questions). All original.

FLASHCARDS.push(
  // h10i-07-1 — Magna Carta & Medieval Challenges
  {id:"h10fc-07-1-6", islandId:"h10i-07-1", front:"What was the Charter of the Forest (1217) and why did it matter?",
   back:"The Charter of the Forest was issued in 1217, two years after Magna Carta, during the reign of the young Henry III.\n\n• It reduced the harsh 'forest law' that reserved huge areas of land for the king's hunting.\n• It restored common people's rights to use royal forests for grazing animals, collecting firewood and gathering food.\n• It removed the death penalty for taking the king's deer.\n\nIt mattered because it extended protections to ordinary people, not just barons, and was reissued alongside Magna Carta many times. Together the two charters limited royal power over both nobles and commoners.", difficulty:2, category:"concept"},
  {id:"h10fc-07-1-7", islandId:"h10i-07-1", front:"How did Simon de Montfort contribute to the growth of Parliament?",
   back:"Simon de Montfort was a baron who led a rebellion against Henry III, who had ignored Magna Carta and ruled poorly.\n\n• After defeating the king at the Battle of Lewes (1264), de Montfort effectively governed England.\n• In 1265 he summoned a parliament that, for the first time, included elected representatives of the towns (burgesses) as well as knights of the shire.\n• This widened who could take part in government beyond the great barons.\n\nDe Montfort was killed at the Battle of Evesham (1265), but his parliament is seen as an important step towards representative government, building on the principle of consent in Magna Carta.", difficulty:3, category:"concept"},
  {id:"h10fc-07-1-8", islandId:"h10i-07-1", front:"Why did the Peasants' Revolt collapse so quickly after Smithfield?",
   back:"The revolt of 1381 fell apart within days of the meeting at Smithfield for several reasons:\n\n• The death of Wat Tyler removed the rebels' main leader and threw them into confusion.\n• Richard II's calm intervention ('I am your captain') persuaded many to disperse peacefully.\n• The rebels had no organised structure or long-term plan once their leaders were gone.\n• The king's forces regrouped and the promises made at Mile End were quickly revoked.\n• Ringleaders such as John Ball were hunted down and executed.\n\nThe collapse showed both the strength of royal authority and the difficulty of sustaining a popular rising without organisation.", difficulty:3, category:"application"}
);
QUESTIONS["h10i-07-1"] = (QUESTIONS["h10i-07-1"] || []).concat([
  {q:"Where was Magna Carta sealed in 1215?", opts:["Runnymede","Nottingham","Smithfield","Evesham"], c:0,
   e:"Magna Carta was sealed at Runnymede, a meadow beside the Thames. Nottingham was where Charles I later raised his standard in 1642, and Smithfield was the site of Wat Tyler's death in 1381 — both belong to different events."},
  {q:"What did the Charter of the Forest (1217) restore to ordinary people?", opts:["The right to vote for MPs","The right to use royal forests for grazing and firewood","Freedom from all taxation","Ownership of all common land"], c:1,
   e:"The Charter of the Forest restored rights to use royal forests, such as grazing animals and gathering wood, easing the harsh forest law. It did not grant voting rights, which only emerged centuries later."},
  {q:"Who summoned the 1265 parliament that first included town representatives?", opts:["King John","Wat Tyler","Simon de Montfort","Henry III himself"], c:2,
   e:"Simon de Montfort summoned the 1265 parliament after defeating Henry III at Lewes. King John, by contrast, was the king forced to seal Magna Carta in 1215 — fifty years earlier."},
  {q:"At which battle was Simon de Montfort killed in 1265?", opts:["Hastings","Lewes","Bosworth","Evesham"], c:3,
   e:"De Montfort won at Lewes (1264) but was killed at Evesham (1265). Hastings (1066) and Bosworth (1485) are different battles from quite different periods."},
  {q:"What was 'villeinage' in medieval England?", opts:["The system that tied peasants to the land and their lord","A tax paid by merchants","A council of barons","A type of royal court"], c:0,
   e:"Villeinage tied peasants to the land under their lord's control, a grievance behind the Peasants' Revolt. It was not a tax or a council; the demand to end it was central to the rebels' cause."},
  {q:"Why did King John's conflict with the Pope weaken him before 1215?", opts:["The Pope sent an army to invade England","England was placed under interdict, undermining his authority","It forced him to abolish all taxes","It gave the barons control of the Church"], c:1,
   e:"John's quarrel with the Pope led to England being placed under interdict, weakening his standing. The Pope did not invade; in fact, he later annulled Magna Carta on John's behalf."},
  {q:"Which statement best explains the SHORT-TERM impact of Magna Carta?", opts:["It immediately created a democratic Parliament","It gave peasants the right to vote","John ignored it within weeks and the Pope annulled it","It permanently ended royal taxation"], c:2,
   e:"In the short term Magna Carta failed: John ignored it and the Pope annulled it, leading to renewed war. Its democratic and constitutional significance grew only over later centuries, not in 1215."},
  {q:"How does the Peasants' Revolt compare with Magna Carta as a challenge to royal power?", opts:["Magna Carta was led by barons; the Revolt was a popular rising by commoners","Both were led by the nobility","Both succeeded fully and permanently","The Revolt came first, then Magna Carta"], c:0,
   e:"Magna Carta (1215) was a baronial challenge, whereas the Peasants' Revolt (1381) was a rising of ordinary people. The Revolt came later, not earlier, marking a shift towards protest from below."},
  {q:"Which factor most directly linked the Black Death to the Peasants' Revolt?", opts:["A new tax on the Church","The king's defeat in France","Labour shortages let surviving peasants demand higher wages, which laws then blocked","A dispute with the Pope"], c:2,
   e:"The Black Death caused labour shortages, so peasants demanded higher wages; the Statute of Labourers blocked this, fuelling anger. The conflict with the Pope belonged to John's reign, not 1381."},
  {q:"Why is the principle that 'the king is subject to the law' seen as the most lasting legacy of Magna Carta?", opts:["It was reused for centuries to justify limiting royal power, including against the Stuarts","It immediately created universal suffrage","It abolished the monarchy in 1215","It only mattered to medieval barons"], c:0,
   e:"The idea that the monarch must obey the law was revived repeatedly, notably against the Stuarts in the 17th century. It did not create universal suffrage or abolish the monarchy, which are much later or unrelated developments."}
]);

FLASHCARDS.push(
  // h10i-07-2 — The English Civil War
  {id:"h10fc-07-2-6", islandId:"h10i-07-2", front:"What was the New Model Army and why was it important?",
   back:"The New Model Army was created by Parliament in 1645 to fight more effectively against the king.\n\n• It was a full-time, professional, national army rather than local forces.\n• Promotion was based on ability, not social rank.\n• It was disciplined, well trained and motivated, many soldiers holding strong Puritan beliefs.\n• Leaders included Sir Thomas Fairfax and Oliver Cromwell (who commanded the cavalry).\n\nIt won the decisive Battle of Naseby (1645), effectively destroying the king's main army. It made Parliament's victory possible and later became a powerful political force in its own right during the Interregnum.", difficulty:2, category:"concept"},
  {id:"h10fc-07-2-7", islandId:"h10i-07-2", front:"What was 'Pride's Purge' (1648) and why did it happen?",
   back:"Pride's Purge took place in December 1648, after the king's defeat in the Second Civil War.\n\n• Many MPs still wanted to negotiate with Charles I rather than put him on trial.\n• The army, determined to bring the king to justice, sent Colonel Thomas Pride to bar or arrest these moderate MPs.\n• Only around 200 MPs who supported trying the king were left — this was the 'Rump Parliament'.\n\nPride's Purge was important because it cleared the way for the trial and execution of Charles I in 1649. It showed the army, not Parliament, now held the real power, raising questions about the legitimacy of what followed.", difficulty:3, category:"concept"},
  {id:"h10fc-07-2-8", islandId:"h10i-07-2", front:"How did the Glorious Revolution (1688) build on the Civil War?",
   back:"The Glorious Revolution settled the long struggle between Crown and Parliament begun by the Civil War.\n\n• The Catholic king James II was replaced by William of Orange and Mary in 1688, with little bloodshed.\n• Parliament, not the king, had effectively invited the new monarchs, asserting its supremacy.\n• The Bill of Rights (1689) stated that the monarch could not raise taxes or keep an army without Parliament's consent, and could not suspend laws.\n\nIt confirmed the lesson of the Civil War that the monarch must rule with Parliament. It established a lasting constitutional monarchy, completing the shift the war had begun.", difficulty:3, category:"application"}
);
QUESTIONS["h10i-07-2"] = (QUESTIONS["h10i-07-2"] || []).concat([
  {q:"What did supporters of the king call themselves during the Civil War?", opts:["Roundheads","Royalists or Cavaliers","Levellers","Diggers"], c:1,
   e:"The king's supporters were Royalists or Cavaliers. Roundheads were the Parliamentarians; the Levellers and Diggers were radical groups that emerged later during the Interregnum."},
  {q:"At which 1645 battle did the New Model Army destroy the king's main army?", opts:["Bosworth","Marston Moor","Naseby","Edgehill"], c:2,
   e:"The New Model Army won decisively at Naseby in 1645. Edgehill (1642) was the indecisive first major battle, and Bosworth (1485) belongs to the Wars of the Roses, not the Civil War."},
  {q:"What was the 'Rump Parliament'?", opts:["The minority of MPs left after Pride's Purge removed the king's would-be negotiators","The first Parliament summoned by Charles I","The Parliament that restored the monarchy in 1660","A council of army generals"], c:0,
   e:"The Rump Parliament was what remained after Pride's Purge in 1648, and it set up the king's trial. The Parliament that restored Charles II in 1660 was a separate, later body."},
  {q:"What belief did the Stuart kings hold that clashed with Parliament?", opts:["That Parliament should choose the monarch","The Divine Right of Kings","That the Pope should rule England","That taxation needed no consent from anyone"], c:1,
   e:"The Stuarts believed in the Divine Right of Kings — that their authority came from God. They did not accept that Parliament should choose the monarch, which is closer to the principle established after 1688."},
  {q:"Who briefly replaced Cromwell as Lord Protector and proved too weak to govern?", opts:["Charles II","Thomas Fairfax","His son Richard Cromwell","William of Orange"], c:2,
   e:"Richard Cromwell briefly succeeded his father but lacked authority, leading to the collapse of the Protectorate. Charles II only returned in 1660, after Richard had already failed."},
  {q:"In what year was the monarchy restored under Charles II?", opts:["1649","1660","1688","1642"], c:1,
   e:"The Restoration of Charles II occurred in 1660. 1649 was the year Charles I was executed, while 1688 was the later Glorious Revolution — distinct turning points."},
  {q:"Why is the trial of Charles I considered a turning point even though the monarchy was later restored?", opts:["It established that a king could be held legally accountable, not just removed by force","It permanently abolished Parliament","It proved the king was above the law","It had no lasting consequences"], c:0,
   e:"For the first time a king was publicly tried and judged, establishing accountability. The Restoration of 1660 did not undo this principle, which resurfaced in the Glorious Revolution of 1688."},
  {q:"How did the Bill of Rights (1689) limit the monarch's power?", opts:["The king lost all power to govern","The monarchy was abolished","The king could not raise taxes or keep an army without Parliament's consent","The king gained absolute control of the courts"], c:2,
   e:"The 1689 Bill of Rights barred the monarch from raising taxes or maintaining an army without Parliament. It limited, rather than abolished, the monarchy, creating a constitutional system."},
  {q:"Which factor best explains why Parliament rather than the king won the Civil War?", opts:["The disciplined, professional New Model Army gave Parliament a military advantage","Parliament had the support of the Pope","The king had no soldiers at all","Foreign armies invaded on Parliament's behalf"], c:0,
   e:"The New Model Army's discipline and promotion by merit gave Parliament the decisive edge at Naseby. There was no papal support or foreign invasion deciding the war."},
  {q:"How does the Glorious Revolution (1688) show continuity from the Civil War?", opts:["Both restored the Divine Right of Kings","Both asserted that the monarch must rule with Parliament, not above it","Both abolished Parliament","Both increased the king's power to tax freely"], c:1,
   e:"Both events confirmed Parliament's supremacy over the Crown, a continuous theme. Neither restored Divine Right; the 1688 settlement firmly rejected the idea of unchecked royal power."}
]);

FLASHCARDS.push(
  // h10i-07-3 — Suffragettes & Workers' Rights
  {id:"h10fc-07-3-6", islandId:"h10i-07-3", front:"Who was Emily Davison and why was her death significant?",
   back:"Emily Davison was a militant suffragette and member of the WSPU.\n\n• At the 1913 Epsom Derby she ran onto the racecourse in front of the king's horse and was fatally injured, dying a few days later.\n• Whether she intended to die or only to disrupt the race is still debated; she carried a return train ticket and a suffragette flag.\n• Her funeral became a huge public procession.\n\nHer death was significant because it generated enormous publicity for the cause, both at home and abroad. To supporters she was a martyr, though some argued such dramatic acts risked alienating moderate opinion.", difficulty:2, category:"concept"},
  {id:"h10fc-07-3-7", islandId:"h10i-07-3", front:"What was the 'Cat and Mouse Act' (1913)?",
   back:"The Cat and Mouse Act was the government's response to suffragette hunger strikes in prison.\n\n• Imprisoned suffragettes refused food, and force-feeding had caused public sympathy and outrage.\n• Its real name was the Prisoners (Temporary Discharge for Ill-Health) Act 1913.\n• Under the Act, hunger-striking prisoners were released when they grew weak, then re-arrested once they had recovered.\n\nIt was nicknamed the 'Cat and Mouse Act' because the government 'played' with prisoners like a cat with a mouse. It avoided the bad publicity of deaths in custody but still allowed the authorities to keep punishing campaigners.", difficulty:2, category:"concept"},
  {id:"h10fc-07-3-8", islandId:"h10i-07-3", front:"How did the Labour Party emerge to represent workers politically?",
   back:"By 1900 many workers felt the existing parties did not represent them.\n\n• Trade unions and socialist societies set up the Labour Representation Committee (LRC) in 1900.\n• Its aim was to get working-class MPs elected to Parliament.\n• In 1906 it won 29 seats and renamed itself the Labour Party.\n• Keir Hardie was an important early leader.\n\nLabour's rise gave workers a political voice to match their industrial action through unions. It linked the union movement to Parliament and would later form governments that built the welfare state, marking a major shift in working-class power.", difficulty:2, category:"application"}
);
QUESTIONS["h10i-07-3"] = (QUESTIONS["h10i-07-3"] || []).concat([
  {q:"Who led the suffragettes (WSPU), founded in 1903?", opts:["Millicent Fawcett","Emmeline Pankhurst","Emily Davison","Annie Kenney"], c:1,
   e:"Emmeline Pankhurst led the militant WSPU. Millicent Fawcett, by contrast, led the peaceful suffragists (NUWSS) — students often confuse the two leaders."},
  {q:"What was the motto of the suffragettes?", opts:["'Deeds not words'","'Not a penny off the pay'","'Liberty or death'","'Bread and roses'"], c:0,
   e:"'Deeds not words' was the WSPU motto, reflecting their militant approach. 'Not a penny off the pay' was the miners' slogan from the General Strike, a different movement."},
  {q:"At which 1913 event did Emily Davison suffer fatal injuries?", opts:["The Kennington Common meeting","The London Dock Strike","The Epsom Derby","A munitions factory accident"], c:2,
   e:"Emily Davison was injured at the 1913 Epsom Derby running in front of the king's horse. Kennington Common was a Chartist gathering of 1848, an earlier and unrelated event."},
  {q:"What did the 'Cat and Mouse Act' (1913) allow the government to do?", opts:["Release hunger-striking prisoners then re-arrest them once recovered","Ban all suffragette meetings outright","Give women the vote temporarily","Force trade unions to disband"], c:0,
   e:"The Cat and Mouse Act let the authorities release weakened hunger strikers and re-arrest them later. It did not grant any votes; women's suffrage came only in 1918."},
  {q:"In which year did women first gain the vote on equal terms with men?", opts:["1918","1928","1900","1945"], c:1,
   e:"The Equal Franchise Act of 1928 gave women the vote on the same terms as men. The 1918 Act had only enfranchised women over 30 who met a property qualification."},
  {q:"Which organisation was founded in 1900 to elect working-class MPs?", opts:["The Labour Representation Committee","The TUC","The NUWSS","The WSPU"], c:0,
   e:"The Labour Representation Committee (1900) became the Labour Party in 1906. The TUC was the trade union federation, while the NUWSS and WSPU were suffrage organisations."},
  {q:"How did women's work in the First World War help them gain the vote?", opts:["It ended the suffragette campaign entirely","It proved their capability and patriotism, making it hard to deny them the vote","It gave women the vote during the war itself","It had no effect on public attitudes"], c:1,
   e:"Women's wartime work in factories and on the land changed attitudes and made denying them the vote politically difficult. The vote came in 1918, after the war, not during it."},
  {q:"Why do some historians argue suffragette militancy was counterproductive?", opts:["It may have alienated moderate supporters and given the government an excuse to refuse","It instantly won the vote in 1903","It united all politicians behind the cause","It removed the need for the suffragists"], c:0,
   e:"Critics argue militancy alienated moderates and let the government refuse to reward 'lawbreaking'. The peaceful suffragists' long campaign remained essential, so militancy did not replace it."},
  {q:"Which best compares the suffragists and suffragettes as routes to change?", opts:["Both used identical methods","Suffragists built broad support slowly; suffragettes won publicity quickly but divided opinion","Suffragettes were peaceful and suffragists violent","Neither contributed to women gaining the vote"], c:1,
   e:"The suffragists built lasting support through patient campaigning, while suffragette militancy grabbed headlines but split opinion. It is wrong to reverse their methods — the WSPU, not the NUWSS, was the militant group."},
  {q:"How did the rise of the Labour Party change working-class power?", opts:["It gave workers political representation in Parliament to match their industrial action","It abolished the trade unions","It removed the vote from workers","It opposed the later welfare state"], c:0,
   e:"Labour gave workers a parliamentary voice alongside union strength and later built the welfare state. It grew out of the unions rather than abolishing them, strengthening working-class influence."}
]);

FLASHCARDS.push(
  // h10i-07-4 — The Great Reform Act & Chartism
  {id:"h10fc-07-4-6", islandId:"h10i-07-4", front:"What was the Peterloo Massacre (1819) and why did it matter?",
   back:"The Peterloo Massacre took place at St Peter's Field in Manchester in 1819.\n\n• A large, peaceful crowd of around 60,000 had gathered to demand parliamentary reform, including a wider vote.\n• Local magistrates ordered the cavalry to break up the meeting.\n• The soldiers charged with sabres, killing around 15 people and injuring hundreds.\n\nThe name mocked the soldiers who had fought at Waterloo. The massacre shocked many and increased anger at an unrepresentative system. It became a powerful symbol of the demand for reform and of government repression, feeding pressure that helped lead to the 1832 Reform Act.", difficulty:2, category:"concept"},
  {id:"h10fc-07-4-7", islandId:"h10i-07-4", front:"What was the Newport Rising (1839)?",
   back:"The Newport Rising was the most serious act of 'physical force' Chartism.\n\n• In November 1839, thousands of Chartists, many of them coal miners and ironworkers, marched on Newport in South Wales.\n• They aimed to free imprisoned fellow Chartists and possibly spark a wider uprising.\n• Soldiers stationed at the Westgate Hotel opened fire, killing around 20 marchers.\n• Leaders such as John Frost were arrested and transported to Australia.\n\nIt followed Parliament's rejection of the first Chartist petition. The rising showed the desperation of some Chartists but also the strength of the authorities, and its failure pushed the movement back towards peaceful 'moral force' methods.", difficulty:3, category:"concept"},
  {id:"h10fc-07-4-8", islandId:"h10i-07-4", front:"How did the Second (1867) and Third (1884) Reform Acts extend the vote?",
   back:"After 1832, the franchise was widened further in stages:\n\n• The Second Reform Act (1867) gave the vote to many working-class men in the towns, roughly doubling the electorate.\n• The Secret Ballot Act (1872) allowed people to vote in private, reducing bribery and intimidation — a long-standing Chartist demand.\n• The Third Reform Act (1884) extended the vote to working men in the countryside too.\n\nThese reforms gradually moved Britain towards a wider male democracy and quietly achieved several Chartist aims. Even so, all women and some poorer men were still excluded until the 20th century.", difficulty:3, category:"application"}
);
QUESTIONS["h10i-07-4"] = (QUESTIONS["h10i-07-4"] || []).concat([
  {q:"What happened at the Peterloo Massacre in 1819?", opts:["Chartists stormed Parliament","Cavalry charged a peaceful reform meeting in Manchester, killing around 15","Miners began a general strike","The king was forced to sign a charter"], c:1,
   e:"At Peterloo, cavalry charged a peaceful crowd demanding reform, killing about 15 people. It was not a Chartist event — Chartism began later, in 1838 — but it fed the wider demand for reform."},
  {q:"Roughly how many rotten and pocket boroughs did the 1832 Reform Act abolish?", opts:["56","6","156","None were abolished"], c:0,
   e:"The 1832 Act abolished 56 rotten and pocket boroughs, redistributing their seats. The figure was substantial, not a mere handful, though many small boroughs still survived."},
  {q:"Which Whig leader's government passed the Great Reform Act of 1832?", opts:["Feargus O'Connor","Earl Grey","William Lovett","Robert Peel"], c:1,
   e:"Earl Grey's Whig government passed the 1832 Act. O'Connor and Lovett were later Chartist leaders, not the ministers responsible for the Reform Act."},
  {q:"What was the Newport Rising of 1839?", opts:["A violent 'physical force' Chartist march that soldiers crushed","A peaceful suffragette demonstration","A miners' strike for higher pay","The first Chartist petition to Parliament"], c:0,
   e:"The Newport Rising was an armed Chartist march, suppressed with around 20 deaths. It was not a suffragette event; the suffrage campaigns came decades later."},
  {q:"What was the difference between 'moral force' and 'physical force' Chartists?", opts:["Moral force wanted votes for women only","Physical force opposed the People's Charter","Moral force favoured peaceful persuasion; physical force hinted at violence","They used identical methods"], c:2,
   e:"Moral force Chartists like Lovett favoured peaceful methods, while physical force Chartists like O'Connor threatened violence. Both supported the Charter, so it is wrong to say one opposed it."},
  {q:"Which Chartist demand was achieved by the Secret Ballot Act of 1872?", opts:["A secret ballot","Annual parliaments","Payment of MPs","Equal-sized constituencies"], c:0,
   e:"The 1872 Secret Ballot Act delivered the Chartist demand for secret voting. Payment of MPs and equal constituencies came through other, later reforms, while annual parliaments was never adopted."},
  {q:"How did the 1832 Reform Act help cause the rise of Chartism?", opts:["By excluding the working class through a property qualification, leaving them feeling betrayed","By giving all men the vote","By abolishing Parliament","By granting women the vote"], c:0,
   e:"The 1832 Act based the vote on property, excluding the working class who felt betrayed and turned to Chartism. It did not grant universal male or female suffrage — those demands drove later protest."},
  {q:"Which best explains why the 1832 Act should not be called 'democratic'?", opts:["It gave everyone the vote","Only about one in five adult men could vote and women were barred","It introduced the secret ballot","It abolished the monarchy"], c:1,
   e:"After 1832 only around one in five men could vote and women were explicitly excluded, so it was far from democratic. The secret ballot only arrived in 1872, not 1832."},
  {q:"Why did Chartism fade after 1848 despite its mass petitions?", opts:["All six demands were granted in 1848","Its leaders joined the government","Parliament rejected the petitions, the movement was divided, and conditions improved","The Newport Rising had succeeded"], c:2,
   e:"Chartism declined because Parliament rejected its petitions, it split over tactics, and improving conditions reduced support. Its demands were achieved gradually later, not all at once in 1848."},
  {q:"How does the gradual extension of the vote (1867, 1872, 1884) show change over time in this study?", opts:["Power shifted slowly from a narrow elite towards a wider male democracy","The franchise shrank back to the aristocracy","Women gained the vote in the 1860s","No further reform happened after 1832"], c:0,
   e:"The later Reform Acts widened the male electorate step by step, quietly achieving Chartist aims. Women, however, remained excluded until the 20th century, so the change was real but incomplete."}
]);

FLASHCARDS.push(
  // h10i-07-5 — Slavery & the Abolition Movement
  {id:"h10fc-07-5-6", islandId:"h10i-07-5", front:"What was the Somerset case (1772) and why was it important?",
   back:"The Somerset case was a famous legal ruling that weakened slavery in England.\n\n• James Somerset was an enslaved man brought to England, who escaped and was recaptured to be shipped abroad.\n• The campaigner Granville Sharp helped bring the case to court.\n• In 1772, the judge Lord Mansfield ruled that no law allowed an enslaved person to be forcibly removed from England against their will.\n\nThe ruling was often understood to mean that slavery had no legal basis on English soil, encouraging the idea that England was 'free'. It gave the abolition movement an important early legal and moral boost, though it did not end the slave trade itself.", difficulty:2, category:"concept"},
  {id:"h10fc-07-5-7", islandId:"h10i-07-5", front:"How did enslaved people themselves resist and help bring about abolition?",
   back:"Enslaved and formerly enslaved people were active agents in ending slavery, not just passive victims.\n\n• On the Middle Passage and on plantations, people resisted through revolts, escape and refusing to work.\n• Large slave rebellions, such as those in the Caribbean (including a major revolt in Jamaica in 1831–32), alarmed the British government and made slavery seem costly and dangerous to maintain.\n• Formerly enslaved writers like Olaudah Equiano shaped public opinion with first-hand testimony.\n\nThis resistance is important because older accounts sometimes credited only white campaigners. Modern history stresses that the actions of enslaved people themselves were a major factor in abolition.", difficulty:3, category:"application"},
  {id:"h10fc-07-5-8", islandId:"h10i-07-5", front:"How did economic arguments and interests affect the abolition campaign?",
   back:"Economics worked both for and against abolition.\n\nAgainst abolition:\n• Slave traders, plantation owners and ports like Bristol and Liverpool profited hugely and resisted change.\n• The 'West India lobby' defended slavery in Parliament.\n\nFor abolition (in some arguments):\n• By the early 1800s some claimed the slave economy was declining or less profitable than 'free' trade.\n• Newer industries did not depend on slavery.\n\nHistorians debate how far economics, rather than morality, ended slavery. Most argue the moral campaign was decisive, but that changing economic interests made abolition easier for Parliament to accept.", difficulty:3, category:"application"}
);
QUESTIONS["h10i-07-5"] = (QUESTIONS["h10i-07-5"] || []).concat([
  {q:"Which British ports grew wealthy from the slave trade?", opts:["Bristol and Liverpool","Newport and Dover","Nottingham and Leeds","Manchester and Birmingham"], c:0,
   e:"Bristol and Liverpool profited enormously as slave-trading ports. Manchester and Birmingham were inland industrial cities better known from the Reform Act debates, not the slave trade."},
  {q:"What did Lord Mansfield rule in the Somerset case of 1772?", opts:["Slavery was legal everywhere in the Empire","No law allowed an enslaved person to be forcibly removed from England","The slave trade was abolished at once","Enslaved people must be compensated"], c:1,
   e:"The 1772 ruling held that no law permitted forcibly removing an enslaved person from England, undermining slavery on English soil. It did not abolish the slave trade, which continued until 1807."},
  {q:"Which campaigner gathered evidence and toured the country exposing the slave trade?", opts:["Thomas Clarkson","William Wilberforce","Aneurin Bevan","Earl Grey"], c:0,
   e:"Thomas Clarkson collected testimony and objects and toured Britain building support. Wilberforce led the campaign in Parliament, while Bevan and Grey belong to entirely different periods."},
  {q:"What was the famous abolitionist image produced by Wedgwood?", opts:["A portrait of the king","A kneeling enslaved man with the words 'Am I not a man and a brother?'","A map of the triangular trade","A picture of a sugar plantation"], c:1,
   e:"The Wedgwood medallion showed a kneeling enslaved man asking 'Am I not a man and a brother?'. It became a powerful campaign symbol, unlike a simple map or plantation scene."},
  {q:"Roughly what proportion of enslaved Africans is estimated to have died on the Middle Passage?", opts:["About one in five","All of them","About one in a hundred","About four in five"], c:0,
   e:"Around one in five enslaved Africans died during the brutal Atlantic crossing. The figure was tragically high but not the majority, and the horror of these deaths fuelled abolitionist campaigning."},
  {q:"Which consumer tactic did abolitionists use to pressure the slave economy?", opts:["A strike of factory workers","A boycott of slave-grown sugar","A refusal to pay taxes","A boycott of foreign cloth"], c:1,
   e:"Abolitionists organised a boycott of slave-grown sugar to hit the trade economically. A tax strike or factory walkout belonged to other movements, such as Chartism or the unions."},
  {q:"Why is it important to recognise the resistance of enslaved people themselves?", opts:["Revolts and resistance pressured the government, so abolition was not only the work of white campaigners","Enslaved people played no part in abolition","It proves the slave trade was profitable","It shows slavery ended without any campaign"], c:0,
   e:"Slave revolts made slavery costly and dangerous to maintain, contributing to abolition. Older accounts wrongly credited only white campaigners, so highlighting this resistance corrects the picture."},
  {q:"Which best explains the difference between the 1807 and 1833 Acts?", opts:["1833 ended the trade; 1807 abolished slavery","1807 ended the trade in enslaved people; 1833 abolished slavery itself","Both abolished slavery completely","Neither changed the law"], c:1,
   e:"The 1807 Act banned the slave trade, while the 1833 Act abolished slavery itself across most of the Empire. Reversing these dates is a common and costly error."},
  {q:"How did the moral campaign most likely combine with economics to bring abolition?", opts:["Economics alone ended slavery with no campaign","Moral pressure was decisive, while changing economic interests made Parliament readier to act","Morality was irrelevant to abolition","The trade became more profitable, encouraging abolition"], c:1,
   e:"Most historians see the moral campaign as decisive, with shifting economic interests making abolition easier to accept. The claim that the trade grew more profitable and so was abolished reverses the logic."},
  {q:"Why was the 1833 Act's treatment of formerly enslaved people controversial?", opts:["Owners were compensated and freedom came through an 'apprenticeship' system","The enslaved were paid large sums","No one was actually freed","It applied only outside the Empire"], c:0,
   e:"The 1833 Act paid compensation to slave owners, not the enslaved, and delayed full freedom through apprenticeship. It did free around 800,000 people, so the claim that no one was freed is wrong."}
]);

FLASHCARDS.push(
  // h10i-07-6 — Trade Unions: Tolpuddle to the General Strike
  {id:"h10fc-07-6-6", islandId:"h10i-07-6", front:"What were the Combination Acts and what changed in 1824–25?",
   back:"The Combination Acts of 1799 and 1800 banned workers from joining together (combining) to demand better pay or conditions.\n\n• They made trade unions effectively illegal during the early Industrial Revolution.\n• Workers caught organising could be imprisoned.\n\nIn 1824 the Combination Acts were repealed, briefly legalising unions, but a wave of strikes alarmed the government. In 1825 a new Act restricted unions again, allowing them to exist but tightly limiting their right to strike.\n\nThis shows the cautious, on-and-off way the law slowly accepted unions, and the deep official fear of organised workers in this period.", difficulty:2, category:"concept"},
  {id:"h10fc-07-6-7", islandId:"h10i-07-6", front:"What was the London Dock Strike of 1889 and why did it matter?",
   back:"The London Dock Strike was a landmark victory for 'New Unionism'.\n\n• Dockers were unskilled, casual workers who were poorly paid and had little security.\n• In 1889 they went on strike demanding the 'dockers' tanner' — a wage of sixpence an hour.\n• Leaders included Ben Tillett, Tom Mann and John Burns.\n• The strike was well organised, won public sympathy and donations, and after several weeks the dockers won their demand.\n\nIt mattered because it showed that even unskilled workers could organise effectively. It inspired a wave of new unions among the lower-paid, broadening the trade union movement beyond skilled craftsmen.", difficulty:3, category:"concept"},
  {id:"h10fc-07-6-8", islandId:"h10i-07-6", front:"What was the significance of the 1927 Trade Disputes Act?",
   back:"The Trade Disputes Act was passed by the Conservative government in 1927, after the failure of the General Strike.\n\n• It made general strikes and sympathetic strikes (striking to support workers in other industries) illegal.\n• It restricted unions' ability to fund the Labour Party.\n• It banned certain public-sector workers from joining unions linked to the TUC.\n\nIts significance was to weaken the unions and punish them for 1926, marking a low point for the movement. The Act was eventually repealed by the post-war Labour government in 1946, showing how the balance of power between unions, employers and government shifted over time.", difficulty:3, category:"application"}
);
QUESTIONS["h10i-07-6"] = (QUESTIONS["h10i-07-6"] || []).concat([
  {q:"What did the Combination Acts of 1799–1800 do?", opts:["Legalised all trade unions","Made it illegal for workers to join together to demand better conditions","Gave workers the vote","Created the TUC"], c:1,
   e:"The Combination Acts banned workers from combining, making early unions effectively illegal. They did the opposite of legalising unions; full legal recognition came only with the 1871 Act."},
  {q:"Who led the Tolpuddle Martyrs in forming their society in 1834?", opts:["George Loveless","Ben Tillett","Feargus O'Connor","Tom Mann"], c:0,
   e:"George Loveless led the Tolpuddle labourers. Ben Tillett and Tom Mann were leaders of the much later 1889 Dock Strike, while O'Connor was a Chartist — different movements and decades."},
  {q:"What wage did the dockers demand in the 1889 London Dock Strike?", opts:["A pound a day","The 'dockers' tanner' — sixpence an hour","No pay cut at all","A share in the docks"], c:1,
   e:"The dockers demanded the 'dockers' tanner', sixpence an hour, and won. The slogan about resisting a pay cut ('Not a penny off the pay') belonged to the miners before the 1926 General Strike."},
  {q:"In which year were trade unions given full legal recognition?", opts:["1834","1871","1926","1799"], c:1,
   e:"The 1871 Trade Union Act gave unions legal recognition. 1834 was the Tolpuddle case, 1799 the Combination Acts, and 1926 the General Strike — all different milestones."},
  {q:"How long did the General Strike of 1926 last before the TUC called it off?", opts:["Nine days","Nine weeks","Nine months","One day"], c:0,
   e:"The General Strike lasted nine days in May 1926 before the TUC ended it. The miners then held out alone until November, but the general action itself was brief."},
  {q:"What did the 1927 Trade Disputes Act make illegal?", opts:["All trade unions","General and sympathetic strikes","Voting in elections","Any wage rise"], c:1,
   e:"The 1927 Act banned general and sympathetic strikes to weaken the unions after 1926. It did not abolish unions entirely, which remained legal under the 1871 Act."},
  {q:"Why are the Tolpuddle Martyrs significant for the trade union movement?", opts:["Their harsh punishment and the mass campaign for their pardon became a symbol of solidarity","They won the right to strike in 1834","They founded the Labour Party","They led the General Strike"], c:0,
   e:"The Martyrs' transportation and the 800,000-signature campaign for their pardon made them lasting symbols of solidarity. They did not win strike rights or found Labour, which came much later."},
  {q:"What was the key difference between 'New Model Unions' and 'New Unionism'?", opts:["They were identical","New Model Unions were skilled craftsmen; New Unionism organised unskilled workers","New Unionism came first","New Model Unions were illegal"], c:1,
   e:"New Model Unions (1850s) were respectable skilled craft unions; New Unionism (1880s) organised unskilled workers like dockers. New Unionism came later, building on the earlier model."},
  {q:"Which factor best explains why the General Strike of 1926 failed?", opts:["The government's careful preparation kept services running and the TUC lost its nerve","The miners had no support at all","Strikes were illegal before 1926","Foreign workers replaced the strikers"], c:0,
   e:"Government preparation and TUC caution doomed the strike. Sympathetic strikes were only banned afterwards, by the 1927 Act, so they were not illegal when the strike began."},
  {q:"How does the repeal of the 1927 Act in 1946 show change over time?", opts:["The balance of power shifted back towards unions under a Labour government","Unions were permanently weakened","The monarchy regained control of strikes","Nothing changed for workers"], c:0,
   e:"The 1946 repeal under Labour restored union rights, showing how power between unions and government shifted over time. It reversed, rather than confirmed, the weakening imposed in 1927."}
]);

FLASHCARDS.push(
  // h10i-07-7 — Twentieth-Century Rights
  {id:"h10fc-07-7-6", islandId:"h10i-07-7", front:"What were the 'five giants' identified by the Beveridge Report (1942)?",
   back:"The Beveridge Report (1942) was a hugely popular wartime plan for social reform. It identified five great social problems — the 'five giants' — that the state should defeat:\n\n• Want (poverty).\n• Disease (ill health).\n• Ignorance (lack of education).\n• Squalor (poor housing).\n• Idleness (unemployment).\n\nEach giant was matched by a planned solution, such as social security against Want and a national health service against Disease.\n\nThe report sold hundreds of thousands of copies and shaped the post-1945 welfare state, providing the blueprint for reforms like the NHS, National Insurance and council housing.", difficulty:2, category:"concept"},
  {id:"h10fc-07-7-7", islandId:"h10i-07-7", front:"What was the Windrush generation and its significance?",
   back:"The Windrush generation refers to people, especially from the Caribbean, who came to Britain after the Second World War.\n\n• The ship Empire Windrush arrived in 1948, symbolising the start of large-scale post-war migration.\n• Many came to help rebuild Britain and fill labour shortages, working in transport, the NHS and industry.\n• They faced racism and discrimination in housing and employment.\n\nTheir significance is that they reshaped British society and made race relations a central issue. Their experiences led to campaigns and to the Race Relations Acts, while their contribution to services like the NHS was vital to post-war Britain.", difficulty:2, category:"concept"},
  {id:"h10fc-07-7-8", islandId:"h10i-07-7", front:"How did opposition from doctors nearly threaten the founding of the NHS?",
   back:"Creating the NHS in 1948 was not straightforward, even after the law was passed.\n\n• Many doctors, represented by the British Medical Association (BMA), opposed the plan.\n• They feared losing their independence and becoming salaried state employees.\n• Some worried about government control over their work.\n\nHealth Minister Aneurin Bevan negotiated and compromised — famously saying he had won the consultants over by 'stuffing their mouths with gold', allowing hospital doctors to keep some private practice.\n\nThis shows that even popular reforms faced strong resistance from powerful interest groups, and that individuals like Bevan had to use political skill to overcome it.", difficulty:3, category:"application"}
);
QUESTIONS["h10i-07-7"] = (QUESTIONS["h10i-07-7"] || []).concat([
  {q:"Which of these was one of Beveridge's 'five giants'?", opts:["Slavery","Squalor","Taxation","Monarchy"], c:1,
   e:"Squalor (poor housing) was one of the five giants, alongside want, disease, ignorance and idleness. Slavery and monarchy were not among them — they belong to earlier parts of this study."},
  {q:"In what year did the Empire Windrush arrive, symbolising post-war migration?", opts:["1928","1948","1968","1906"], c:1,
   e:"The Empire Windrush arrived in 1948, the same year the NHS was founded. 1928 was the Equal Franchise Act and 1906 the start of the Liberal reforms — different milestones."},
  {q:"What did the Old Age Pensions Act of 1908 provide?", opts:["A small weekly pension for people over 70","Free healthcare for all","Unemployment benefit for everyone","Free secondary education"], c:0,
   e:"The 1908 Act gave a modest weekly pension to people over 70. Free healthcare came only with the NHS in 1948, decades later."},
  {q:"Which 1968 strike helped lead to the Equal Pay Act?", opts:["The London Dock Strike","The General Strike","The Ford Dagenham sewing machinists' strike","The Newport Rising"], c:2,
   e:"The 1968 Ford Dagenham strike by women machinists pushed for equal pay, leading to the 1970 Act. The Dock Strike (1889) and General Strike (1926) were earlier and about different issues."},
  {q:"What did the Sex Discrimination Act of 1975 do?", opts:["Gave women the vote","Banned discrimination on grounds of sex in employment, education and services","Created the NHS","Made unions illegal"], c:1,
   e:"The 1975 Sex Discrimination Act outlawed sex discrimination in work, education and services. Women already had the vote (from 1918 and 1928), so it did not concern suffrage."},
  {q:"Who led the Bristol Bus Boycott of 1963?", opts:["Paul Stephenson","Aneurin Bevan","Millicent Fawcett","Keir Hardie"], c:0,
   e:"Paul Stephenson led the Bristol Bus Boycott against the refusal to employ black or Asian bus crews. Bevan founded the NHS and Hardie led early Labour — different campaigns."},
  {q:"How did the Second World War help bring about the welfare state?", opts:["It made reform impossible","Shared wartime sacrifice created public demand for a fairer society","It ended interest in social welfare","It abolished the Beveridge Report"], c:1,
   e:"The shared hardship of war built support for a fairer post-war society, helping create the welfare state. The Beveridge Report (1942) shaped this demand rather than being abolished."},
  {q:"Which best explains the significance of the NHS founded in 1948?", opts:["It made healthcare free at the point of use and confirmed the state's duty to its citizens","It only helped the wealthy","It charged high fees for treatment","It was quickly abolished"], c:0,
   e:"The NHS made healthcare free at the point of use, transforming access for ordinary people and marking a wider role for the state. It was funded by taxation, not high fees, and endured."},
  {q:"How do the Liberal reforms (1906–14) show continuity with the later welfare state?", opts:["Both accepted that the state had a duty to help the vulnerable","Both blamed the poor for their own poverty","Both abolished all benefits","Both applied only to the wealthy"], c:0,
   e:"The Liberal reforms began the shift towards state responsibility for the vulnerable, which the post-1945 welfare state extended. They moved away from blaming the poor, marking continuity in the role of government."},
  {q:"How does Bevan's struggle with doctors over the NHS illustrate the 'factors' theme?", opts:["An individual's political skill was needed to overcome opposition from a powerful interest group","Individuals never mattered to change","Doctors had no influence on the NHS","War alone created the NHS without any individuals"], c:0,
   e:"Bevan's negotiation shows how individuals had to overcome resistance even when conditions favoured reform. It demonstrates the interplay of individuals and other factors, not that any single one acted alone."}
]);

FLASHCARDS.push(
  // h10i-07-8 — Factors & Continuity in Protest
  {id:"h10fc-07-8-6", islandId:"h10i-07-8", front:"How can you compare the importance of different factors in a synoptic answer?",
   back:"AQA's thematic study rewards weighing factors against each other across the whole period c1170–present.\n\nA strong approach:\n• Identify which factors drove a change (individuals, ideas, war, economy, government).\n• Argue which mattered most in that case, and why.\n• Show how factors worked together — for example, individuals usually succeeded only when ideas, war or the economy created the right conditions.\n• Compare across the period: war was decisive for women's suffrage and the welfare state, while the economy drove the Peasants' Revolt and Chartism.\n\nThe best answers reach a judgement rather than simply listing factors, and support it with examples from across the centuries.", difficulty:3, category:"application"},
  {id:"h10fc-07-8-7", islandId:"h10i-07-8", front:"How have methods of protest changed and stayed the same across the period?",
   back:"Looking across c1170–present reveals both continuity and change in how people protested.\n\nContinuity:\n• Petitions appear again and again — from the Peasants' Revolt to the Chartists, abolitionists and the Tolpuddle campaign.\n• Mass meetings and marches recur, as at Peterloo, Kennington Common and suffrage rallies.\n• Violence or its threat appears at times, from 1381 to the Newport Rising.\n\nChange:\n• Methods became more organised and national, helped by printing, the railways and later the press.\n• Peaceful, legal campaigning and use of the vote gradually became the main route to change.\n\nProtest broadened from local revolt to organised national movements.", difficulty:3, category:"application"},
  {id:"h10fc-07-8-8", islandId:"h10i-07-8", front:"Why did some protests succeed while others failed, across the period?",
   back:"Comparing protests across the whole study shows several reasons for success or failure.\n\nProtests were more likely to succeed when:\n• They won broad public support and good organisation (abolition, the 1889 Dock Strike).\n• Wider factors helped, such as war or economic change creating pressure.\n• Government was willing or forced to concede (the 1832 Act).\n\nProtests often failed in the short term when:\n• They were divided or poorly organised (Chartism, the General Strike).\n• Government was strong and prepared (1926) or determined to repress (Tolpuddle, Peterloo).\n\nMany 'failures' still mattered in the long term, as their demands were later achieved, showing change was usually slow and hard-won.", difficulty:3, category:"application"}
);
QUESTIONS["h10i-07-8"] = (QUESTIONS["h10i-07-8"] || []).concat([
  {q:"Which factor was most decisive in causing the welfare state after 1945?", opts:["War, as shared wartime sacrifice created demand for a fairer society","An individual acting entirely alone","Medieval ideas of justice","Falling profits from the slave trade"], c:0,
   e:"The Second World War acted as a catalyst, building demand for a fairer society. While individuals like Beveridge and Bevan mattered, war created the conditions, and the slave trade is unrelated to 1945."},
  {q:"Which is an example of an INDIVIDUAL driving change in this thematic study?", opts:["The Black Death","William Wilberforce leading the abolition campaign","The Industrial Revolution","The Beveridge Report's five giants"], c:1,
   e:"Wilberforce is an individual who drove change. The Black Death and Industrial Revolution are economic factors, while the five giants are ideas, not a person."},
  {q:"How did war act as a catalyst in BOTH 1215 and 1918?", opts:["Military pressure helped force Magna Carta, and war work helped women win the vote","War prevented all change in both years","Both wars were against the same enemy","War only mattered in the 20th century"], c:0,
   e:"Military failure in France pressured John in 1215, and women's war work helped win the vote in 1918, both showing war as a catalyst. War clearly mattered well before the 20th century."},
  {q:"Which is the best example of CONTINUITY in methods of protest across the period?", opts:["The monarch always granting demands at once","The repeated use of mass petitions, from 1381 to the Chartists and abolitionists","Protest always being peaceful","Petitions being used only in the 20th century"], c:1,
   e:"Mass petitions recur throughout the period, a clear continuity. Protest was not always peaceful, nor were petitions confined to the 20th century — they appear as early as 1381."},
  {q:"How did IDEAS contribute to protest across different periods?", opts:["Ideas only mattered after 1945","From medieval notions of justice to Enlightenment liberty and modern equality, ideas justified demands for change","Ideas never influenced any protest","Only economic ideas ever mattered"], c:1,
   e:"Ideas of justice, liberty and equality inspired protest from John Ball to abolitionists to civil rights campaigners. Ideas operated throughout the period, not only after 1945."},
  {q:"Which best describes the overall CHANGE in the role of government across the period?", opts:["From defending the established order to actively extending rights and welfare","From extending welfare to opposing all reform","From democracy to absolute monarchy","No change occurred at all"], c:0,
   e:"Government shifted from resisting demands to driving reform through the welfare state and rights laws. This reverses the idea of moving towards absolute monarchy, which describes the opposite direction."},
  {q:"Why is it a mistake simply to list events in a synoptic 'factors' answer?", opts:["Listing events always gains full marks","The question rewards linking and comparing factors across the period, not retelling each protest","Events are irrelevant to history","Only dates matter in such answers"], c:1,
   e:"Synoptic answers reward comparing factors across the whole period rather than narrating events one by one. Examples support the argument, but dates alone or simple lists do not meet the demand."},
  {q:"How did the ECONOMY help cause protest in both 1381 and the 1830s?", opts:["Labour shortages after the Black Death, then industrialisation, shifted power and fuelled demands","The economy was stable and unchanging throughout","Only war ever caused protest","The economy only affected the 20th century"], c:0,
   e:"The Black Death's labour shortages drove the Peasants' Revolt, and industrialisation fuelled reform demands in the 1830s. Economic change repeatedly shifted power, well before the 20th century."},
  {q:"Why did many protests that 'failed' still matter in the long term?", opts:["Failure meant they had no lasting impact","Their demands were often achieved later, as with Chartism's five points","They were all immediately successful","Only successful protests ever influenced change"], c:1,
   e:"Movements like Chartism failed at the time but saw most demands achieved later, showing long-term significance. Treating 'failures' as having no impact misjudges how slow, cumulative change worked."},
  {q:"Which statement best reflects a balanced judgement on the 'factors' that drove change?", opts:["No single factor dominated; change usually came from factors working together","Individuals alone explain every change","War alone explains every change","Government always blocked all change"], c:0,
   e:"The strongest judgement is that factors combined — individuals succeeded when ideas, war, the economy or government created the conditions. Crediting any single factor for everything oversimplifies the period."}
]);
